Appendix A Description of the Project and Responsibilities Appendix B Title and Risk of Loss Appendix C [REDACTED] Appendix D [REDACTED] Appendix E [Reserved] Appendix F [REDACTED] OPERATION AND MAINTENANCE AGREEMENT THIS OPERATION AND MAINTENANCE AGREEMENT (this "Agreement") is entered into and effective as of June 12, 2015 (the "Execution Date"), by and among Otter Tail Power Company ("OTP"), a corporation organized and existing under the laws of the State of Minnesota, Montana-Dakota Utilities Co. ("MDU"), as Owners; and MDU, in its capacity as Maintenance Provider; and OTP, in its capacity as Control Center Authority. RECITALS A. The Owners are constructing the Project and the Discretely Owned Substation Assets associated therewith to: (i) enhance service reliability for electric customers in North Dakota, South Dakota and the MISO territories; (ii) strengthen the transmission network to meet additional demands for electric power; and (iii) enhance transmission system capacity to support the installation of renewable energy resources; B. Contemporaneously herewith, the Owners have entered into: (i) the Project Ownership Agreement; (ii) the Discretely Owned Substation Assets Transmission Capacity Exchange Agreement; (iii) the Construction Management Agreement; and (iv) such other agreements as the Owners have deemed necessary; C. The Owners wish to provide for the efficient and reliable: (i) exercise of day-to-day operational control of the Project, utilizing the existing resources of the Owners to the maximum extent possible and (ii) performance of maintenance, repair, restoration and other services for the Project; D. The Owners desire to enter into this Agreement with the Control Center Authority to provide day-to-day operational control of the Project and the Control Center Authority desires to provide such services over the Project in accordance with the terms and subject to the conditions of this Agreement; and E. The Owners desire to enter into this Agreement with the Maintenance Provider to: (i) assure a seamless transition from construction to commercial operation of the Project and (ii) provide maintenance, repair, restoration and other services, and the Maintenance Provider desires to assure such transition and to provide such services in accordance with the terms and subject to the conditions of this Agreement for the Project. AGREEMENT In consideration of the foregoing recitals, the mutual covenants set forth in this Agreement and other good and valuable consideration, the receipt and sufficiency of which is hereby acknowledged, each Owner and each Responsible Entity agrees as follows. ARTICLE 1 DEFINITIONS 1.1 Definitions . In addition to the other terms defined herein, the following terms, whether in the singular or in the plural, when used herein; in Schedule 1, Generally Applicable Provisions; in the appendices attached hereto; or in notices given under this Agreement and initially capitalized, have the meanings specified below: "Affiliate" means any Person that, directly or indirectly, through one or more intermediaries, controls, is controlled by or is under common control with, a Party. "Agency Authority" has the meaning given in Section 2.4. "Agreement" means this Operation and Maintenance Agreement, as it may be supplemented or amended. "Applicable Energy Regulations" means the rules, Orders, regulations, practices, procedures and protocols established in compliance with Applicable Law by applicable Transmission Providers (such as the Midwest Independent Transmission System Operator, Inc.), electric reliability organizations (such as the North American Electric Reliability Corporation and the Midwest Reliability Organization) and comparable Persons that are applicable to the Maintenance Services, the Control Center Services, the Construction Work, the Discretely Owned Substation Assets, the Project or the performance of the obligations of the Parties under this Agreement. "Big Stone South Substation" means the substation owned by OTP and described on Exhibit C of the Project Ownership Agreement, which substation is not part of the Project. "Billing Cycle" has the meaning given in Section 6.2.1. "BSSE Design Criteria Guidelines" means the requirements established in Appendix C, as such requirements are amended by the Management Committee. "Budget Deadlock" has the meaning given in Section 7.2. "Budget Overrun" means any expenditure or the incurrence of a Capital Expense or an Operating Expense (contingent or realized) that will or would reasonably be expected to cause a then current Final Budget to be exceeded. "Business Day" means any day other than a Saturday, Sunday or federal holiday. "Capital Expenses" means expenses incurred in connection with Capital Improvements. "Capital Improvements" means capital additions or modifications to the Project that are undertaken after the applicable In-Service Date and will be funded by the Owners according to Ownership Percentages pursuant to Section 4.4.1(x) of the Project Ownership Agreement in accordance with a Final Budget. Capital Improvements include Modifications that are required by Applicable Law, but exclude (i) work undertaken pursuant to the Project Ownership Agreement or the Construction Agreements in accordance with the Project Plan, (ii) Upgrades, and (iii) Non-Project Modifications. "Cause" has the meaning given in Section 13.2.1.2. "CEII" has the meaning given in Section 12.6.2. "Change in Law" means any change in, or enactment of, any Applicable Law or official published policy regarding the interpretation or enforcement of any Applicable Law by a Governmental Body that takes place after the Effective Date and affects or relates to the Maintenance Services, the Control Center Services or the performance of the obligations of one or more Owners or one or more Responsible Entities under this Agreement, including the imposition of any new Governmental Approval requirements; provided, however, a change in Applicable Law affecting only a tax payable or any other cost of performance hereunder will not constitute a Change in Law. "Changed Circumstance" means a: (i) Force Majeure or (ii) change in the scope of the Maintenance Services or the Control Center Services directed by the Management Committee that was not contemplated in the current expense forecast or Final Budget at the time such forecast was provided or such Final Budget was approved by the Management Committee, which change impairs the ability of the applicable Responsible Entity to perform its obligations with respect to the Project within the applicable forecast or Final Budget. "Confidential Information" has the meaning given in Section 12.1. "Construction Agreements" means all contracts, agreements or arrangements establishing the terms of performance of any part of the Construction Work but specifically excluding (i) the Project Ownership Agreement, (ii) the Construction Management Agreement, (iii) the Real Property Agreements and (iv) construction contracts arising from the Substation Work. "Construction Management Agreement" means that certain Construction Management Agreement, by and between the Owners and the Construction Manager, effective as of the Effective Date. "Construction Manager" means OTP, solely in its capacity as Construction Manager under the Construction Management Agreement, and permitted successors or assigns. Reference to the Construction Manager excludes any reference to the Construction Manager in any other capacity. "Construction Work" means all activities that are necessary, desirable or incidental to placing the Project in service and achieving Final Completion in accordance with Good Utility Practice and the Project Plan, other than: (i) the services to be provided under the Construction Management Agreement by the Construction Manager and (ii) the obligations of the Owners (individually or collectively through the Management Committee) under the Construction Management Agreement. "Contractor" means any Person with whom the Owners or the Construction Manager enter into a Construction Agreement. Reference to an Owner as a "Contractor" excludes any reference to such Owner in any other capacity. "Control Center Authority" means the Person designated as the "Control Center Authority" in this Agreement, which Person, when acting under this Agreement in such capacity, will have day-to-day operational control over the Project, including a Person that executes a joinder in a form acceptable to such Person and the Management Committee to become a Control Center Authority hereunder. Reference to a Control Center Authority excludes any reference to a Control Center Authority in any other capacity. "Control Center Costs" has the meaning given in Section 4.2. "Control Center Records" has the meaning given in Section 5.12.2. "Control Center Services" has the meaning given in Section 2.2. "Damages" means any loss, charge, deficiency, tax, fine, interest, assessment, judgment, award, demand, liability, penalty or costs and expenses, including amounts paid in settlement, reasonable attorneys' and other professional fees and reasonable costs of investigation. "Debt" means for any Person, without duplication: (i) indebtedness of such Person for borrowed money; (ii) obligations of such Person evidenced by bonds, debentures, notes, mortgages or other similar instruments; (iii) obligations of such Person to pay (a) amounts due under financing leases; (b) the deferred purchase price of Property or services (other than accounts payable in the ordinary course of business); or (c) amounts due under capitalized or operating leases; (iv) obligations of such Person under direct or indirect guarantees in respect of, and obligations (contingent or otherwise) of such Person to purchase or otherwise acquire, or otherwise to assure a creditor against loss in respect of, indebtedness or obligations of another Person; (v) obligations of such Person under interest rate or currency protection agreements or other hedging instruments; (vi) obligations of such Person to purchase securities (or other Property) that arise out of, or in connection with, the sale of the same or substantially similar securities (or Property); or (vii) deferred obligations of such Person to reimburse any bank or other Person in respect of amounts paid or advanced under a letter of credit or other instrument. "Discretely Owned Substation Assets" means that portion of the Big Stone South Substation and the Ellendale 345 kV Substation, each as identified in Exhibit C of the Project Ownership Agreement. Discretely Owned Substation Assets will not constitute part of the Project. "Discretely Owned Substation Assets Transmission Capacity Exchange Agreement" means that certain Discretely Owned Substation Assets Transmission Capacity Exchange Agreement by and between the Owners, effective as of the Effective Date. "Discretely Owned Substation Owner" means an Owner that owns a Discretely Owned Substation Asset. "Easement" means the easements described in the Real Property Agreements. "Effective Date" means the Execution Date. "Ellendale 345kV Substation" means the substation owned by MDU and described as the Ellendale 345 kV Substation on Exhibit C of the Project Ownership Agreement. "Emergency" means any circumstance or condition that will or could imminently be expected to materially harm the safe and reliable operation of all or a portion of the Project, the Transmission Grid or otherwise endanger public safety, Property or the environment. "Engineering and Operating Committee" or "E&O Committee" means the Engineering and Operating Committee established pursuant to the Project Ownership Agreement, which committee has been delegated authority by the Management Committee to undertake the obligations and exercise the rights accorded to it under this Agreement. "Equipment" means any product that: (i) is to be incorporated into the Project; (ii) is an assembly of operational or non-operational parts, whether motorized or manually operated; and (iii) requires service connections such as wiring. "FERC" means the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission, a regulatory Governmental Body of the United States, or any successor thereto. "FERC Standards of Conduct" has the meaning given in Section 12.6.1. "Final Budget" has the meaning given in Section 7.1. "Final Completion" with respect to the Project means the determination by the Management Committee that "Final Completion" thereof has been achieved in accordance with Section 11.4 of the Construction Management Agreement. "Final Completion Date" means the date determined in accordance with Section 11.4 of the Construction Management Agreement as the date on which Final Completion of the Project occurs. "Final Order" means an Order as to which: (i) no request for stay is pending before the issuing Governmental Body, no such stay is in effect and, if any deadline for filing any such request is designated by Applicable Law, such deadline has passed; (ii) no petition for rehearing or reconsideration of such action is pending before the issuing Governmental Body and if any deadline for filing any such petition is designated by Applicable Law, such deadline has passed; (iii) the issuing Governmental Body does not have the action under reconsideration on its own motion; and (iv) no appeal to a court, or request for stay by a court, of the issuing Governmental Body's action is pending or in effect and, if any deadline for filing any such appeal or request is designated by Applicable Law, such deadline has passed. "Financial Records" has the meaning set forth in Section 7.10.1. "Financial Summary Report" means a Financial Summary Report delivered pursuant to Section 7.9.2 in substantially the form approved from time to time by the Management Committee. "Financing" means: (i) Debt on terms acceptable to an Owner, the proceeds of which are intended to be used, in whole or in part, to finance the costs of construction of the Project (including Capital Improvements that become part of the Project), (ii) Debt as to which the Liens (including Permitted Owner Liens) of one or more Financing Parties have previously been perfected and which Liens will attach to or encumber that Owner's Ownership Percentage, (iii) Debt heretofore or hereafter secured under a mortgage, deed of trust or security agreement or instrument which grants a lien on substantially all of the tangible property of either Owner, or (iv) any refinancing, renewal, or continuation, in whole or in part, of any of the foregoing. "Financing Parties" means any and all lenders, bondholders, underwriters and financing institutions, including credit enhancers and institutional investors, providing or facilitating a Financing and any trustee(s) or agent(s) acting on any of their behalf and any successors, assigns or other transferees of any of the foregoing. "Financing Party Agent" means any Person designated by a Financing Party to provide advice to such Financing Party with respect to the condition, operation or maintenance of the Project as it relates to an Owner that has or will receive Financing from such Financing Party. "First Responder Services" has the meaning set forth in Section 3.1. "Force Majeure" means the occurrence of an event or series of events that is beyond the reasonable control of the Person affected that hinders the performance under contract of such Person and does not result from the fault, negligence, intentional misconduct or willful misconduct of the affected Person or such Person's failure to comply with Applicable Law or Good Utility Practice; and such event or series of events could not have been avoided by the affected Person through the exercise of reasonable diligence, including the expenditure of reasonable monies and/or taking reasonable precautionary measures, including (to the extent that such events satisfy the foregoing criteria), the following: (i) acts of God or the public enemy; (ii) expropriation or confiscation of Project Property; (iii) war, terrorism, rebellion, sabotage, civil unrest or riot; (iv) fires, explosions, hurricanes, floods, tornadoes, microbursts, other abnormally severe weather events or other natural catastrophes; (v) actions or inaction of a Governmental Body; (vi) a Change in Law; (vii) conditions at, on or affecting the Project Real Property that could not have been reasonably anticipated, including the existence of Hazardous Substances or archeological materials; (viii) operating conditions on the Transmission Grid, including Emergencies; and (ix) strikes and other labor disturbances. Under no circumstance will an event of Force Majeure excuse a Person's obligations to make payments when due under this Agreement unless such Force Majeure event results in a failure of the Federal Reserve wire system or other failure of the banking system that deprives a Person of access to otherwise available funds. "Funding Amount" has the meaning given in Section 6.1. "GAAP" means generally accepted accounting principles practiced in the United States of America, as in effect from time to time, applied on a consistent basis. "Good Reason" has the meaning given in Section 13.2.1.4. "Good Utility Practice" means any of the practices, methods or acts engaged in or approved by a significant portion of the electric utility industry in the region during the relevant time period, or any of the practices, methods and acts which, in the exercise of reasonable judgment in light of the facts known at the time the decision was made, could have been expected to accomplish the desired result at a reasonable cost consistent with good business practices, reliability, safety and expedition in a manner that: (i) is consistent with Applicable Law; (ii) makes due consideration for reliability, safety and protection of Equipment and Materials and the Project and the Transmission Grid; and (iii) is consistent with manufacturer's recommendations and warranties. Good Utility Practice is not intended to be limited to the optimum practice, method or act to the exclusion of all others, but rather to be a range of acceptable practices, methods or acts generally accepted in the region. "Governmental Approvals" means all waivers, franchises, variances, permits, authorizations, certificates, licenses and Orders of or from any Governmental Body having jurisdiction over the Owner, the Maintenance Provider, the Control Center Authority, the Maintenance Services, the Control Center Services or any portion of the Project, as may be in effect from time to time. "Governmental Body" means any: (i) nation, state, county, city, town, village, district or other jurisdiction of any nature; (ii) federal, state, local, municipal, tribal, foreign or other government; or (iii) governmental or quasi-governmental authority of any nature (including any governmental agency, branch, board, commission, department, instrumentality, office or other entity, and any court), in any such case exercising, or entitled to exercise, administrative, executive, judicial, legislative, police, regulatory or taxing authority or power of any nature over this Agreement, any part of the Project, the performance of the Maintenance Services and Control Center Services, the Construction Work, the Discretely Owned Substation Assets, the Project Real Property, the Construction Manager or any of the Parties. To the extent available, on a timely basis, the percentage change will be calculated using the final adjusted value for the applicable date of determination. If such final adjusted value is unavailable on a timely basis, then the preliminary value for the date of determination will be used and subsequently adjusted when the final adjusted value for such date is published. If such final adjusted value is subsequently determined to be incorrect, then it will be adjusted when the corrected final adjusted value for such date is published. ARTICLE 2 ENGAGEMENT AND MOBILIZATION 2.1 Engagement of Maintenance Provider . Each Owner hereby appoints and retains the Maintenance Provider, on the terms and conditions set forth herein, to provide the services set forth in Article 3, the other provisions of this Agreement, as applicable to a Maintenance Provider (the "Maintenance Services"), with respect to the Project set forth in Appendix A. The Maintenance Provider hereby accepts such appointment and, except as provided in Section 2.3, agrees to perform the Maintenance Services as an independent contractor. In providing the Maintenance Services, the Maintenance Provider recognizes the necessity of a close working relationship among the Maintenance Provider, the Control Center Authority, the Transmission Provider and the Owners. The fact that an Owner is serving in any other capacity under this Agreement or as a Transmission Provider does not in any way change, modify or release such Owner from its rights, interests and obligations in its capacity as an Owner under this Agreement. 2.2 Engagement of Control Center Authority . Each Owner hereby appoints and retains the Control Center Authority, on the terms and conditions set forth herein, to provide the services set forth in Article 4 and the other provisions of this Agreement, as applicable to the Control Center Authority (the "Control Center Services") with respect to the Project set forth in Appendix A. The Control Center Authority hereby accepts such appointment and agrees to perform the Control Center Services as an independent contractor. In providing the Control Center Services, the Control Center Authority recognizes the necessity of a close working relationship among the Maintenance Provider, the Control Center Authority, the Discretely Owned Substation Owners, the Transmission Providers and the Owners. The fact that an Owner is serving in any other capacity under this Agreement or as a Transmission Provider, does not in any way change, modify or release such Owner from its rights, interests and obligations in its capacity as an Owner under this Agreement. 2.3 Agency Authority . Subject to the terms and conditions set forth in this Agreement, each Owner designates and appoints the Maintenance Provider as its designated and disclosed agent to carry out, on behalf of such Owner, the following services and the Maintenance Provider accepts such appointment and agrees to execute such authority and to act on behalf of each Owner as such Owner's agent with respect to the following: (i) purchasing of Equipment, Materials and Services from Third Parties; (ii) undertaking day-to-day ministerial operational activities and making day-to-day ministerial operational decisions relating to the Easements in the ordinary course of business, including (a) authorizing payments to landowners for amounts to be paid in connection with the Real Property Agreements; (b) authorizing payments for Damages to landscaping, roads and driveways, livestock, crops, fields and other landowner Property caused in connection with the maintenance of the Project; (c) approving or denying landowner requests to plant trees or construct other improvements within the Project Real Property, in accordance with Good Utility Practice; and (d) obtaining insurance relating to the Project Real Property; (iii) amending the Real Property Agreements to correct non-substantive errors or to match the actual location of the transmission facilities with the legally described Project Real Property areas; and (iv) undertaking any other ministerial matters relating to the Real Property Agreements. 2.4 Agency Authority Limited . The applicable Maintenance Provider's agency authority to act as agent for and on behalf of each Owner is specifically set forth in Section 2.3 ("Agency Authority"). No authority to act as an agent hereunder is created, implied or bestowed on a Maintenance Provider by this Agreement for any other purpose whatsoever. In those matters where a Maintenance Provider will exercise Agency Authority and act as the agent for and on behalf of the Owners: (i) the Maintenance Services will be undertaken as a disclosed agent for and on behalf of each of the Owners and (ii) the Agency Authority of the Maintenance Provider is limited to binding the Owners severally (and not jointly), except with the prior written consent of the Management Committee. Without limiting the foregoing, a Maintenance Provider is expressly not authorized to: (i) mortgage, grant Liens against or otherwise encumber the Project Real Property; (ii) transfer, assign or otherwise dispose of any interests in the Project Real Property; or (iii) appear on behalf of the Owners in litigation relating to the Project Real Property. The Owners, acting through the Management Committee, retain the right to further limit the scope of Agency Authority granted in Section 2.3. 2.5 Mobilization . 2.5.1 Commencement of Services . Although this Agreement is effective as of the Effective Date, the Parties recognize that services to be provided under this Agreement will not be needed until a reasonable time prior to energization of the Project ("Project In-Service Date") and then are likely only to be necessary from the Maintenance Provider and the Control Center Authority with assigned responsibility for maintenance or operation of the Project as set forth in Appendix A (each, a "Responsible Entity"). 2.5.2 Plans . The E&O Committee, in coordination with the Responsible Entities shall develop an: (i) initial rolling five (5) Operating Year scheduled maintenance plan (the "Scheduled Maintenance Plan") and (ii) initial inventory plan ("Inventory Plan"). Both the initial Scheduled Maintenance Plan and the initial Inventory Plan must be accompanied by forecasts of the annual cost thereof as prepared by the Maintenance Provider. The Maintenance Provider shall include within the forecasted cost of Scheduled Maintenance Services, a forecasted annual contingency for the performance of Unscheduled Maintenance Services. A Maintenance Provider may amend the portion of the Scheduled Maintenance Plan as it relates to the associated forecast on notice to each member of the E&O Committee. The Scheduled Maintenance Plan and the Inventory Plan may be amended by the E&O Committee from time to time. ARTICLE 3 MAINTENANCE SERVICES AND OTHER OBLIGATIONS 3.1 Maintenance Services . From and after the Project In-Service Date, the Maintenance Provider shall provide, with respect to the services for which it is responsible as specified on Appendix A, substantially similar services with respect to the Project that it provides for its own transmission lines, including vegetation management, outage scheduling services, security and other planned services (the "Scheduled Maintenance Services"); maintenance, repair and restoration services that become necessary, but are not scheduled (the "Unscheduled Maintenance Services"); and first responder services, such as observation, inspection and assessment services, at the request of a Control Center Authority, to determine the physical condition of the Project, switching and other services in the event of an Emergency to isolate equipment in support of system restoration or to maintain safety until the Maintenance Provider can complete permanent repairs to the Project ("First Responder Services") and such other services as are provided for in this Agreement or otherwise agreed to by the Maintenance Provider and the E&O Committee. 3.1.1 Scheduled Maintenance Plan . 3.1.1.1 Annual Update. No later than June 1 of each Operating Year after the Project In-Service Date, the Maintenance Provider shall prepare a recommended update to its portion of the Scheduled Maintenance Plan and the associated annual expense forecast (including a forecasted contingency for Unscheduled Maintenance Services) of the cost thereof for the immediately following five (5) Operating Years and deliver it to each member of the E&O Committee. The E&O Committee will review the Maintenance Provider's update in cooperation with the Maintenance Provider and prepare a consolidated updated Scheduled Maintenance Plan. 3.1.1.2 Subsequent Changes. The Maintenance Provider shall notify the E&O Committee of any material changes required in the Scheduled Maintenance Plan (together with any change in the forecasted cost thereof) as promptly as possible after learning of the necessity of such changes. 3.1.2 First Responder Services . 3.1.2.1 Performance of First Responder Services. Maintenance Provider shall use Good Utility Practice to plan for and schedule staffing and equipment sufficient for twenty-four (24) hours per day, seven (7) days per week availability for First Responder Services. When a Control Center Authority requires a Maintenance Provider to perform First Responder Services, the Control Center Authority shall contact the individual designated by the Maintenance Provider (or its Local Agent) on the Master Notification List. 3.1.2.2 Maintenance Provider Responsibilities. Upon the request of the Control Center Authority, Maintenance Provider shall mobilize to perform the First Responder Services and shall use commercially reasonable efforts to perform such services within the time frame requested by the Control Center Authority in accordance with the terms and conditions of this Agreement. Such Maintenance Provider shall provide status reports as reasonably requested by the Control Center Authority. Maintenance Provider and the Control Center Authority shall promptly notify each other of any material change in the timeframe needs or estimates, together with the reason for such change. 3.1.3 Inventory and Warehousing . 3.1.3.1 Requirements. To the extent not otherwise made available to it by the Construction Manager, Maintenance Provider shall procure the Inventory required for the performance of its Maintenance Services in accordance with the Inventory Plan. To the extent applicable, Inventory procured by Maintenance Provider shall comply with BSSE Design Criteria. Maintenance Provider shall prepare and provide to the E&O Committee on request, a forecast for the type, number and warehousing locations for Inventory, a reconciliation of the Inventory levels and any recommendations for changes thereto to the E&O Committee. 3.1.3.2 Inventory Plan. At the request of the E&O Committee, the Maintenance Provider shall deliver an update to the Inventory Plan for the next two (2) Operating Years to the E&O Committee. As part of each Services Plan Review, the E&O Committee will review all updates to the Inventory Plan in consultation with the Maintenance Provider. The E&O Committee will develop a consolidated updated Inventory Plan for the Project by August 1 of such Operating Year. The Maintenance Provider shall implement the updated Inventory Plan. 3.1.3.3 Reserved. 3.1.3.4 Owner's Inventory. Maintenance Provider may, but is not obligated to, use spare parts, materials or equipment from other Inventories it maintains in connection with its other business operations that are unrelated to the Project; provided, that if any such items are used for the Project, the replacement cost thereof constitutes a Maintenance Cost and will be reimbursed in accordance with the provisions of Appendix D. 3.1.3.5 Surplus Inventory. Subject to Section 3.10, Inventory procured exclusively for the Project and paid for by the Owners but no longer needed by a Maintenance Provider should be disposed of at the direction of the E&O Committee. 3.1.4 Capital Improvements . At the request of the E&O Committee, the Maintenance Provider responsible for Capital Improvements shall undertake or arrange for the engineering, procurement, construction or installation of such Capital Improvements to the extent specified in the Final Budget. The E&O Committee and such Maintenance Provider shall work together to establish written guidelines, requirements and protocols that will govern the performance of and payment allocation for such Capital Improvements. 3.2 Costs . 3.2.1 Maintenance Costs . Except as otherwise provided in this Agreement, the costs incurred by a Maintenance Provider in the performance of the Maintenance Services ("Maintenance Costs") will be reimbursable in accordance with Appendix D and include, without duplication, the following: (i) amounts incurred by a Maintenance Provider in connection with the performance of the Maintenance Services with respect to the Project, as determined in accordance with Appendix D; (ii) amounts due to Third Party contractors (including subcontractors), consultants, legal counsel and other Persons performing portions of the Maintenance Services in connection and in accordance with this Agreement; (iii) costs related to the acquisition of Equipment and Materials, including Inventory in accordance with the Inventory Plan; (iv) costs of premiums, deductibles and self-insured retentions for Project Insurance, to the extent such Project Insurance is (a) required by Appendix F and (b) specifically designated as a Maintenance Cost by the terms of Appendix F (except as otherwise provided in Appendix D) or by action of the Management Committee; (v) costs of a Maintenance Provider attributable to the Maintenance Services and relating to discharging and paying any liability, loss, Damage or expense, including attorneys' fees and other costs of defending, settling or otherwise administering Third Party Claims or Third Party Environmental Claims, except to the extent the Maintenance Provider is obligated to indemnify the Owners pursuant to Section 11.1.2; (vi) sales and use taxes and other taxes arising from and payable to any Governmental Body, payments in lieu of taxes, and fees related to Governmental Approvals, arising out of the performance of the Maintenance Services, Real Property Agreements or otherwise attributable to the performance of the Maintenance Services, excluding income, gross receipts, franchise or taxes similarly imposed or assessed on the results of operations of a Maintenance Provider or either Owner; (vii) any other costs incurred by Maintenance Provider attributable to the performance of the Maintenance Services, including (net of any reductions or adjustments received with respect thereto) rental charges, royalties and fees, professional services fees and costs incurred in connection with, or arising out of, performance bonds, security, utilities, safety, transport, storage and telecommunications; (viii) costs that are (a) stated to be Maintenance Costs pursuant to this Agreement or (b) determined by the Management Committee to be Maintenance Costs; (ix) costs incurred in connection with winding-up activities, as described in Section 13.2.2.4, and costs incurred in connection with termination of a Maintenance Provider, as described in Section 13.2.2.5; (x) payments to landowners for amounts required by the Management Committee to be paid after the term of the Construction Management Agreement in respect of any of the Real Property Agreements. 3.2.2 Costs Not Chargeable to Project . The provisions of Section 3.2.1 to the contrary notwithstanding, the following do not constitute Maintenance Costs: (i) costs of a Maintenance Provider associated with the preparation or negotiation of (a) the Project Agreements or amendments thereto or (b) the commercial terms and conditions of any subcontract with an Affiliate or amendments or change orders thereto; (ii) costs incurred by either Owner in performing functions of the Management Committee, the E&O Committee or any other committee established pursuant to any of the Project Agreement and expenses of its personnel while performing such functions; (iii) costs of insurance (including premiums, deductibles and self-insured retentions) purchased by any individual Owner, except as specifically provided in Appendix F, as it may be amended by the Management Committee; (iv) costs incurred by Maintenance Provider in connection with its indemnification obligations set forth in Article 11; (v) the cost of complying with conditions specified in any Governmental Approval obtained by an Owner granted or issued by Final Order that are not generally applicable to the Owners collectively but are imposed on an individual Owner; (vi) without duplication of the costs described in clause (iv) above, costs that arise from a Maintenance Provider's failure to perform its obligations in accordance with this Agreement, which failure is the result of the Maintenance Provider's willful misconduct or intentional misconduct; and (vii) costs that are excluded as Maintenance Costs by the express terms of this Agreement. 3.2.3 Insurance Proceeds Not Constituting Maintenance Costs . To the extent that proceeds of insurance required to be procured pursuant to Appendix F are paid or recovered in respect of Maintenance Costs, such proceeds will be deducted or offset against the amount of Maintenance Costs incurred therefor. 3.3 Standard of Care . The Maintenance Provider shall perform the Maintenance Services and maintain the Project in a prudent, efficient and careful manner using such Maintenance Provider's judgment based on its experience in maintaining, repairing and restoring transmission facilities and in all material respects in accordance with: (i) Applicable Law; (ii) Good Utility Practice; (iii) this Agreement and the Interconnection Agreements; (iv) the requirements of applicable insurance policies then in effect and which have been secured by or provided to the Maintenance Provider for the Project or the Maintenance Services or the Control Center Services; and (v) the Real Property Agreements. 3.4 Instructions and Reliance . Meetings may be telephonic. Maintenance Provider may defer action (to the extent practicable) that is dependent upon such discussion or instruction pending such meeting or receipt of instructions from the Management Committee or E&O Committee, as appropriate. 3.5 [REDACTED]

The Maintenance Provider shall enforce the applicable warranties as necessary on behalf of the Owners. ARTICLE 4 CONTROL CENTER SERVICES AND OTHER OBLIGATIONS 4.1 Control Center Services . The Control Center Authority shall perform the Control Center Services in a prudent, efficient and careful manner using the Control Center Authority's judgment based on its experience in operating transmission facilities and in all material respects in accordance with: (i) Applicable Law; (ii) Good Utility Practice; (iii) this Agreement; and (iv) the requirements of applicable insurance policies then in effect that have been secured by or provided to the Control Center Authority for the Project or the Control Center Services. Each Responsible Entity acknowledges the importance of: (i) compliance with Applicable Law and (ii) diligent implementation of procedures designed to meet such standards. The Owners and the Responsible Entities agree to comply with the provisions of Applicable Law. Upon the request of a Responsible Entity, each other Party shall provide the applicable Responsible Entity with information in its possession that such Responsible Entity may reasonably require to fulfill its obligations under this Section 5.1. 5.2 Change in the Scope of Maintenance Services . The Management Committee may, at any time, request an adjustment to the scope of Maintenance Services to be provided by Maintenance Provider hereunder. Any such adjustment in the scope of Maintenance Services must be in writing and signed by the affected Parties. In the event of any material change in the scope of services to be provided by a Responsible Entity hereunder, the applicable expense forecast, the Final Budget, or both, and, if applicable, the Scheduled Maintenance Plan, will be equitably adjusted. 5.3 Governmental Approvals . Each Responsible Entity shall take whatever actions are necessary or desirable (as determined by the E&O Committee) to maintain or otherwise fulfill the performance and compliance requirements under and in connection with the Governmental Approvals with respect to the Project. Each Owner shall provide its support, cooperation and assistance in connection therewith. 5.4 Insurance Obligations . Each Responsible Entity shall comply with applicable insurance obligations imposed on it in Appendix F, as it may be modified by the Management Committee from time to time. 5.5 Timely Performance . Each Responsible Entity shall notify the E&O Committee promptly of any circumstance that has become known to such Responsible Entity that has or will have the potential to limit the ability of such Responsible Entity to timely perform the Maintenance Services or Control Center Services, as applicable. Any such Responsible Entity shall identify any actions that it has taken or proposes to take to overcome any such circumstance. 5.6 Transmitting Data . Prior to the Project In-Service Date, the Maintenance Provider and the Control Center Authority shall establish the categories of data that the Maintenance Provider will provide to the Control Center Authority and the means, methods and protocols pursuant to which such data must be transmitted. The Maintenance Provider shall thereafter transmit the required data in accordance therewith. 5.7 Services Plan Review . The E&O Committee shall convene, and the Responsible Entities shall attend, periodic meetings not less frequently than annually, at mutually agreeable times and places, to, among other things, review the performance of Maintenance Services, Control Center Services, compliance with Applicable Law, opportunities for efficiencies and cost savings in connection therewith (each, a "Services Plan Review"). Services Plan Review meetings may be held telephonically. The initial agenda for each such meeting will be proposed by the E&O Committee. Any Responsible Entity may suggest additional items for the agenda and the E&O Committee will amend the agenda to include such items. 5.8 Technical Guidelines . Except as otherwise specified by the E&O Committee, a Responsible Entity shall use and comply with the technical guidelines applicable to the other transmission facilities owned by the Responsible Entity in the region. 5.9 Safety and Training Programs . Continuing throughout the Term, each Responsible Entity shall train its personnel in any and all services to be performed by such Responsible Entity under this Agreement. The Responsible Entity shall provide sufficient training to assure that, as is applicable to the tasks assigned, its personnel are knowledgeable of Applicable Energy Regulations and Good Utility Practice and are capable of performing in compliance therewith. 5.10 Material Adverse Events . If there is a Changed Circumstance, an Emergency or a Third Party Claim (whether insured or uninsured) ("Material Adverse Event") that affects the performance of its services under this Agreement, the Responsible Entity shall give prompt written notice of the occurrence of such Material Adverse Event and provide its assessment of the impact thereof to the E&O Committee. If the additional costs caused by a Material Adverse Event are expected to cause the Final Budget to be exceeded, the E&O Committee may request that the Management Committee expedite a vote to consider whether to approve such Budget Overrun. Adjustments arising from Material Adverse Events will be specifically identified and the Maintenance Provider shall provide detailed information concerning the actual impact of each such Material Adverse Event and amount expended as a result thereof together with each subsequent Invoice until the full impact of such Material Adverse Event is known and incurred. 5.11 Labor and Personnel . The Responsible Entity shall provide and make available all labor and professional managerial field service, administrative and other personnel as are reasonably necessary to perform the services required of it hereunder, which may be the employees of the Responsible Entity, its Affiliates or subcontractors. Each Responsible Entity shall appoint a project representative ("Project Representative") that will have oversight responsibility for the performance of services hereunder. Each Responsible Entity shall identify the Project Representative (and associated contact information) on the Master Notification List. Each Responsible Entity will be bound by the written communications, directions, requests and decisions made by its Project Representative. 5.12 Service Records . 5.12.1 Retention of Maintenance Records . The Maintenance Provider shall, in accordance with its standard document retention practices, keep and retain, or cause to be kept and retained: (i) the as-built drawings and the portions of the Project Design Book provided to it by the Construction Manager, including currently-marked drawings showing the location of all portions of the Project for which it is providing Maintenance Services; (ii) maintenance and repair records for the Project; (iii) records required to be maintained pursuant to Applicable Energy Regulations with respect to the Project; (iv) all Maintenance Subcontracts and all invoices, amendments and change orders thereto (collectively, "Maintenance Subcontract Documents"); (v) all records relating to Project Insurance or claims thereunder in which the Maintenance Provider is involved; and (vi) other documents related to the performance of the Maintenance Services as requested by the E&O Committee ("Maintenance Records"). 5.12.2 Retention of Control Center Records . The Control Center Authority shall, in accordance with its standard document retention practices, keep and maintain or cause to be kept and maintained for inspection by either Owner or its designated representatives: (i) logs, SCADA System data and similar information and (ii) records required to be maintained pursuant to Applicable Energy Regulations ("Control Center Records"). 5.12.3 Inspection . Subject to Applicable Law, each Responsible Entity shall make all Maintenance Records or Control Center Records it is required to retain under this Agreement available for inspection and audit by either Owner at such Responsible Entity's principal place of business or other agreed location. Each Owner, at its own expense, will be entitled to audit or otherwise inspect (and copy) such records during business hours on at least five (5) Business Days' notice to the Responsible Entity. Each Owner agrees that it will endeavor to coordinate its requests for inspection or audit with the other Owners and the Responsible Entities, as applicable, agree to cooperate with such audit or inspection upon request. 5.13 End of Term Obligations . Upon expiration of the Term, or any earlier termination of the services of any Responsible Entity, certain of the services required of such Responsible Entity may not have been entirely performed and additional services may be necessary. Accordingly, upon the request of the E&O Committee, each Owner and each Responsible Entity agrees to negotiate the terms and conditions for specific post-termination transition services on substantially the same payment and liability terms as are set forth in this Agreement. ARTICLE 6 FUNDING FOR SERVICES 6.1 Payment . Each Responsible Entity is entitled to be reimbursed for Maintenance Costs or Control Center Costs expended by it in the performance of the Maintenance Services or the Control Center Services, as appropriate (the "Funding Amount"), except as expressly otherwise provided herein. Subject to Section 14.2, a Responsible Entity shall: (i) be responsible for costs incurred by it in the performance of the Maintenance Services or the Control Center Services, as appropriate, that arise from its willful misconduct, or intentional misconduct and (ii) not seek reimbursement from the Owners for such costs. To the extent applicable to its compensation hereunder, each Maintenance Provider shall accurately record, on a daily basis, the type of services performed on behalf of the Owners, the employment classification of the individuals performing such services and the time spent by each such individual. 6.2 Invoices . 6.2.1 Invoices . Except as otherwise provided hereunder, Responsible Entities will be entitled to submit Invoices to each Owner on a periodic basis to be determined by the E&O Committee (the "Billing Cycle"). Each Responsible Entity should submit an Invoice for the services performed hereunder by the twentieth (20th) day following the end of each Billing Cycle. In addition, if the Management Committee directs a Maintenance Provider to make payments to landowners in connection with the Real Property Agreements, the Management Committee shall provide such Maintenance Provider with the schedule of such payments that are to be made in each Operating Year. A Maintenance Provider will be entitled to invoice each Owner for its Ownership Percentage of such payments reasonably in advance of the date on which such payments are to be made to landowners. Each Owner shall remit the invoiced amount to an invoicing Maintenance Provider in accordance with Section 6.4. 6.2.2 Supporting Documentation . Subject to Section 7.10.2, within ten (10) days of the submission of each Invoice, the Maintenance Provider shall provide the following information to the extent reasonably available to it: (i) the basis for the amount invoiced in accordance with the provisions of Appendix D for Maintenance Services or Section 4.2 for Control Center Services, as applicable; (ii) sales and use tax information as required by the Owners. (iii) documentation reasonably required by an Owner to identify asset replacements and associated values for tax or accounting purposes; and (iv) such other information as may be reasonably requested by the E&O Committee. If information requested pursuant to clause (iii) or (iv) is not reasonably available at the time it submits its Invoice, the Responsible Entity shall submit such information with its next succeeding Invoice. 6.2.3 Limited Representations . The delivery of an Invoice by a Responsible Entity constitutes a representation to the Owners that: (i) the services reflected in such Invoice have been performed; (ii) any Equipment and Materials reflected as having been delivered have been delivered; and (iii) the amounts reflected as having been paid have been paid. The foregoing representations are subject to specific qualifications expressed by the Responsible Entity in any such Invoice. 6.3 Accounts . Each Invoice must specify with particularity the account (and all other relevant information) to which the Owners are to make payments in respect to that Invoice. The Owners will be entitled to rely on the accuracy of the information provided by the Responsible Entity. A Responsible Entity's books and records of account with respect to the provision of services hereunder and the cost thereof must be current, complete, true and correct in all material respects. All such books and records must be organized, indexed and kept in a consistent manner. 6.4 Payments . Except with respect to those amounts properly withheld or offset hereunder, each Owner shall make full payment, in immediately available funds, of its Ownership Percentage of the amounts invoiced by the Responsible Entity in Invoices. Payments are to be made by the twentieth (20th) day following receipt of the Invoice. 6.5 Final Payment . Within ninety (90) days after the termination of this Agreement with respect to any Responsible Entity, such Responsible Entity shall submit a final Invoice to each Owner that documents amounts due hereunder through the date of termination together with any termination amount permitted pursuant to Section 13.2.2. 6.6 Notice of Dispute and Withholding . Without prejudicing an Owner's other rights under this Agreement, for purposes of determining the amount of payment to which the Responsible Entity is entitled in respect of an Invoice hereunder, an Owner shall promptly notify the Responsible Entity concerning any invoiced amount or portion thereof that it disputes (including where the Owner contends that there is a deficiency with respect to such Invoice or the accompanying documentation) and the basis for such dispute as soon as reasonably practicable with the objective of allowing time to resolve such dispute prior to the date on which payment with respect to the disputed matter would otherwise be due; provided, however, except as provided in the next sentence, an Owner must make timely payment of invoiced amounts pending resolution of disputed amounts. An Owner also may, after issuing a notice to the Responsible Entity, withhold all or any portion of any payment: (i) in accordance with Section 6.8 or (ii) to such extent of an undisputed overdue amount due to such Owner from the Responsible Entity under this Agreement. 6.7 Payment Not Acceptance . Payments hereunder will neither constitute acceptance of the services provided by a Responsible Entity nor foreclose any right of audit or dispute with respect to such payments. Except as provided in Section 6.6 or 6.8, no Owner will withhold any amounts, including disputed amounts, from its payments in respect of an Invoice. Upon audit or other discovery, the applicable Responsible Entity shall refund any amount paid by an Owner in excess of amounts properly due hereunder within fifteen (15) Business Days of demand therefor, together with interest on such excess amount accrued from the date of the excess amount was paid to and including the date it is refunded calculated at a floating rate equivalent to the Responsible Entity's cost of funds for short-term borrowings. 6.8 Optional Payment by Owners . If a Maintenance Provider defaults or neglects to fulfill its obligation to make undisputed payments of amounts required to be paid to a Third Party under any Maintenance Subcontract, then the Owners (acting collectively through the E&O Committee) may cause such obligation to be satisfied by paying such amounts. To the extent the amount of such payments has previously been paid to such Maintenance Provider, the Owners may set off such amounts against the Funding Amount next due by the Owners to such Maintenance Provider. 6.9 Amounts to be Deposited . Within fifteen (15) Business Days of receipt, a Maintenance Provider shall pay to the Owners, by depositing the following sums as directed by the E&O Committee: (i) funds recovered from Maintenance Subcontractors and other counterparties, including backcharges and Damages, for payments previously made by the Owners except with respect to amounts recovered in respect of an indemnification obligation owed to the Responsible Entity on the part of a Maintenance Subcontractor or other counterparty; (ii) proceeds of the sale of surplus Equipment and Materials; and (iii) any other amounts received by a Maintenance Provider arising out of or in connection with this Agreement, which amounts are to accrue to the benefit of the Owners, collectively. ARTICLE 7 FINANCIAL MATTERS AND REPORTS 7.1 Final Budget . Not later than June 1 of each Operating Year, each Responsible Entity shall deliver to the E&O Committee a five (5)-year budget describing Capital Expenses for Capital Improvements that they recommend and the Operating Expense anticipated to be incurred by it for each year, for inclusion in the E&O Committee's consolidated Proposed Budget as required by the Project Ownership Agreement. If the Management Committee does not approve the Proposed Budget, the E&O Committee will work with the Responsible Entities to promptly re-submit a revised consolidated Proposed Budget to the Management Committee for its approval. Once the Management Committee approves a consolidated Proposed Budget, it becomes the Final Budget binding on the Maintenance Provider and Control Center Authority, subject to amendment by vote of the Management Committee from time to time and subject to Section 7.3. 7.2 Budget Deadlock . If by December 1 prior to any Operating Year after the Effective Date, the Management Committee does not approve a Final Budget for the next Operating Year (a "Budget Deadlock"), then for the forthcoming Operating Year, until the Management Committee approves such budget, the unapproved budget proposed will not be implemented but the Final Budget for such Operating Year, as applicable, previously approved by the Management Committee as part of the five (5) year rolling Final Budget process will remain in full force and effect until the Management Committee votes to approve a new Final Budget. If the applicable Operating Year is not covered by a Final Budget, then to the extent necessary, until a new Final Budget is approved, the Operating Expense portion of Final Budget currently in effect will continue in effect as adjusted by changes in the Inflation Factor from the commencement of the then-current Operating Year plus the cost of Capital Improvements that are required for the Project to be maintained so as to meet the requirements of Applicable Law. 7.3 Limitation on Expenditures . Except as provided below, each Final Budget is intended to constitute the control document for the Responsible Entitles pursuant to which the Responsible Entities may incur Capital Expenses. No Responsible Entity may incur Capital Expenses or Operating Expenses that will cause a Budget Overrun, unless: (i) pursuant to an Approved Budget Variance in accordance with Section 7.5; (ii) in connection with a Material Adverse Event; or (iii) necessary for compliance with Applicable Law (including without limitation Modifications that are required by Applicable Law). 7.4 Expense Forecast Overruns . If at any time during an Operating Year, a Responsible Entity anticipates that its forecast of the annual cost of providing Maintenance Services or Control Center Services, as applicable, is no longer accurate, it shall promptly notify the E&O Committee, specify the underlying facts and circumstances and provide an updated forecast of the amounts that are to be reimbursed by the Owners. 7.5 Final Budget Overruns . If a Responsible Entity or the E&O Committee has notified the Management Committee that it anticipates a Budget Overrun, the Management Committee will issue written directions to such Responsible Entity with respect to how it is to proceed within thirty (30) days after the date on which the Management Committee received such notification. The Management Committee is not obligated to authorize a proposed Budget Overrun, except to the extent necessary to ensure an equitable adjustment in the Final Budget to reflect the reasonable value of any increased costs incurred in connection with a Material Adverse Event or as otherwise required to ensure compliance with Applicable Law. If the Management Committee does not approve an overrun request, the E&O Committee shall provide express direction to such Responsible Entity of the actions to be taken or refrained from by way of reducing services to be provided so as to allow the Responsible Entity to be able to operate within the Final Budget. If a Responsible Entity does not believe that the direction provided by the E&O Committee will allow it to perform its obligations in accordance with Section 3.3, such Responsible Entity may, by written notice, decline to further perform the affected obligations and the Management Committee shall thereafter find a replacement provider. If the Management Committee approves such Budget Overrun, such approval will constitute an "Approved Budget Variance," which will contain a detailed description of the changes to the Final Budget required thereby. 7.6 Meetings . At a Party's request, any Responsible Entity and the E&O Committee shall meet, among other things: (i) to review the performance of services under this Agreement and to discuss any expense forecast, the Final Budget, or both, the status of any Scheduled Maintenance Plan or any Inventory Plan; (ii) to discuss any Material Adverse Event and the impact thereof on expense forecasts, the Final Budget, or both, the Scheduled Maintenance Plan or the Inventory Plan, as applicable; or (iii) to review the costs incurred pursuant to Section 8.8. 7.7 Not Responsible for Forecasts . The expense forecasts and the Final Budget prepared by a Responsible Entity represent its reasonable commercial judgment as to the amounts reflected therein in light of its experience and the application of estimation practices consistent with Good Utility Practice. Each Owner acknowledges that the Responsible Entities (individually or collectively) that seek reimbursement hereunder do not have control over the cost of labor, materials, equipment, competitive bidding or market or negotiating conditions pursuant to which the assumptions in such forecasts and the Final Budget relate. Accordingly, no Responsible Entity warrants or represents that bid results, negotiated prices or the monetary impact of Material Adverse Events or Unscheduled Maintenance Services will be accurately forecasted or budgeted. The Responsible Entities will not be liable to either Owner for the inaccuracy of any such expense forecast or Final Budget. 7.8 Prudency Review Undertaking . The applicable Responsible Entity shall provide reasonable assistance and documentation to the Owners (individually or collectively) in connection with any prudency review or similar process relating to matters within the scope of this Agreement in order to address the issues identified by any reviewing Person, including any Governmental Body. Subject to Section 4.2, as applicable, services under this Section 7.8 provided for the benefit of less than all of the Owners will be charged to and payable by each such individual Owner benefiting from the performance of such services. To the extent services provided under this Section 7.8 are provided to the Owners collectively, the costs of providing such services are Maintenance Costs or Control Center Costs, as applicable. 7.9 Reporting Obligations . 7.9.1 Maintenance Reports . The Maintenance Provider shall prepare and furnish to the E&O Committee for submission to the Management Committee a report (each a "Maintenance Report") within fifteen (15) days following the close of each calendar quarter following the Project In-Service Date (or at such other times as may otherwise be directed by the E&O Committee) regarding maintenance of the Project. The E&O Committee, in cooperation with the Maintenance Provider, will develop the form and format for the Maintenance Report and identify the specific topics (e.g., safety, major repairs, Capital Improvements, and warranty items) to be reported upon. 7.9.2 Financial Summary Reports . Each Responsible Entity shall deliver to the E&O Committee a Financial Summary Report substantially in a form approved by the Management Committee, quarterly or as more particularly provided by the E&O Committee. Except as otherwise required by the E&O Committee, the Financial Summary Report will provide: (i) a summary of actual Maintenance Costs or Control Center Costs, as appropriate, that have been incurred during the Operating Year and that are to be reimbursed by the Owners; (ii) a comparison of actual costs to date to the then current forecast and updated forecasted costs to the then current forecast; and (iii) the amount of and explanation for any funds deposited in accordance with Section 6.9. The Maintenance Provider shall, when applicable, provide similar data with respect to Capital Improvements. The E&O Committee is entitled to modify the form of the Financial Summary Report at any time. 7.10 Financial Record Retention and Audit . 7.10.1 Financial Record Retention . Each Responsible Entity submitting Invoices hereunder shall, in accordance with its standard document retention practices, keep and retain, or cause to be kept and retained with respect to the Project: (i) payroll records, daily time sheets and other related personnel records related to the performance of services hereunder; (ii) Maintenance Subcontract Documents; (iii) agreements (together with amendments and change orders), invoices, receipts and similar documentation (other than Maintenance Subcontract Documents) for Maintenance Services or Equipment and Materials purchased for use in connection with the Project, including Master Contracts; (iv) any other records and books of account, records of monies expended, obligations incurred, credits accrued or that otherwise relate to the Project, including documents used by the Responsible Entity to accumulate financial and statistical data in connection with services performed under this Agreement; and (v) with respect to a Control Center Authority that presents Invoices to the Owners, such books and records as will reasonably allow the Owners to determine the fairly allocated actual cost of the Control Center Authority's performance of such services ("Financial Records"). 7.10.2 Record Availability . Each Responsible Entity shall make all Financial Records it is required to retain under this Agreement pursuant to Section 7.10.1 available to the Owners or the Independent Accountants for inspection (and copying) and audit. Such Financial Records will be available at the Responsible Entity's principal place of business or other agreed location upon at least five (5) Business Days' notice. Responsible Entities shall not be required to make Financial Records (other than Maintenance Subcontract Documents) available to either Owner if such availability is restricted in accordance with a protocol adopted by the Management Committee designed to avoid use of such information by the receiving Owner in manner that could violate Applicable Law. 7.10.3 Independent Audit . The Management Committee or an Owner is entitled to engage a public accounting firm experienced in utility accounting (the "Independent Accountants") to conduct an audit and prepare a report of Maintenance Costs, Capital Expenses and, if applicable, Control Center Costs expended or incurred under this Agreement during any fiscal period. To the extent applicable, such reports must be prepared in accordance with GAAP; provided, however, interim internal financial reports may be presented subject to year-end adjustments and may lack footnotes and other required GAAP presentation items. The Management Committee shall concurrently furnish any report of the Independent Accountants prepared at the direction of the Management Committee to each Owner promptly following receipt. The Owners and Responsible Entities shall reasonably cooperate with the Independent Accountants. If the results of any such audit indicate that a reconciliation of amounts paid or received by any Party is necessary, the Independent Accountants shall provide a reconciliation statement to each Party indicating the amounts to be paid or received, if any, by each Party. Subject to dispute resolution procedures, the Parties shall promptly make the payments required by the reconciliation statement within fifteen (15) Business Days of receipt of such reconciliation statement. 7.11 Final Completion Report . Each Responsible Entity shall prepare and concurrently distribute to the Management Committee and each Owner a Final Completion report within a commercially reasonable period of time following termination of this Agreement as to such Responsible Entity, which must include a complete cost report for the Maintenance Services or Control Center Services, as applicable, performed during the last twelve (12) Months, together with a documentation of any amounts that may be due to such Responsible Entity upon termination as provided in Sections 13.2.2.5 and 13.2.2.6. ARTICLE 8 OWNERS' RIGHTS AND DUTIES 8.1 Owners Act Through Committee . Oversight and management of matters arising under this Agreement by the Owners will, except as otherwise provided in this Agreement, be determined by the Management Committee or, to the extent of its delegated authority, the E&O Committee. 8.1.1 Restriction on Rights, Duties and Responsibilities of the Management Committee . Notwithstanding anything to the contrary in this Agreement, neither the Management Committee nor the E&O Committee will have the power or authority to direct the means, manner or methodology used by any Maintenance Provider to carry out the Maintenance Services or a Control Center Authority to carry out the Control Center Services. 8.1.2 Rights . Each Owner and, by delegation, the Management Committee and the E&O Committee (unless otherwise indicated below), have: (i) the right to receive such information (subject to Section 7.10.2) from the Maintenance Provider and Control Center Authority as an Owner, the Management Committee or the E&O Committee may reasonably request; (ii) the right to inspect the Project during the Term at reasonable times without unduly hindering ongoing performance of the Maintenance Services, which right will extend to the Owners and to their respective invitees, including Financing Parties, and Financing Party Agents (as required in connection with an Owner's Financing); and (iii) the right to inspect and audit Maintenance Records maintained by the Maintenance Provider under this Agreement and Control Center Records maintained by the Control Center Authority. 8.1.3 Management Committee . In all matters concerning or arising under this Agreement that require instruction or a vote of the Management Committee to be effective, each Owner will be bound by the written communications, directions, requests and decisions made by the Management Committee. 8.1.4 E&O Committee . In all matters concerning or arising under this Agreement that require instruction or decision of the E&O Committee to be effective, each Owner will be bound by the written communications, directions, requests and decisions made by the E&O Committee. 8.2 Authorized Personnel . Each Owner, Maintenance Provider and Control Center Authority, in its respective capacity, shall identify on the Master Notification List the names and contact information of the individuals who are authorized to sign documents such as contracts, certificates, Governmental Approvals and affidavits on their behalf and to fully bind such Person(s) to the provisions of such documents. 8.3 Property Interests . All Property of the Owners (which includes any and all rights and licenses, express or implied) that arise as a result of the performance of the Maintenance Services and the Control Center Services accrues to the benefit of the Owners as set forth in the Project Agreements. During the Term, each Owner hereby authorizes the Maintenance Provider to use all such Property rights and interests relating to the Project for which it is responsible as necessary for the Maintenance Provider to properly perform the Maintenance Services on such terms as approved and permitted by this Agreement and the other Project Agreements. 8.4 Owner Governmental Approvals and Licenses . Each Owner shall comply with any condition applicable solely to it under the terms of any Governmental Approval that becomes a Final Order and the costs and expenses associated with compliance with such condition(s) will be the sole liability and obligation of such Owner. 8.5 Owner's Insurance Requirements . The Owners shall comply with the insurance obligations imposed on the Owners in Appendix F, as it may be modified by the Management Committee from time to time. 8.6 Right to Carry Out Services . If a Responsible Entity fails to perform Maintenance Services or Control Center Services in accordance with this Agreement and fails, within a thirty (30) day period after receipt of written notice from the E&O Committee, to commence and continue correction of such default or neglect with diligence and promptness, the E&O Committee may, after such thirty (30) day period, give the Maintenance Provider a second written notice to correct such deficiencies within a second fifteen (15) day period. If a Maintenance Provider fails to commence and continue to correct such deficiencies within such second fifteen (15) day period, the E&O Committee may, without prejudice to other remedies it may have hereunder, arrange for the correction of such deficiencies and will be entitled to recover the costs and expenses incurred (which amounts constitute Maintenance Costs) in furtherance thereof from the Maintenance Provider to the extent such Maintenance Provider has been paid any amounts therefor. 8.7 Required Information . An Owner shall provide information requested by a Maintenance Provider that is known and readily available to it, including specifications, documents and drawings of existing above ground structures and facilities, subsurface conditions (including plats or borings identifying the position of cables, lines, pipes or other underground objects) or other conditions relevant to the performance of the Maintenance Services. The information so provided is furnished as a courtesy and the Owner providing it does not guarantee the accuracy of such information and is not liable for any inaccuracy or omission therein contained, except to the extent of its willful misconduct or intentional misconduct. 8.8 E&O Committee Functions . The provisions of this Agreement require the E&O Committee from time to time to, among other things, consolidate expense forecasts or Proposed Budgets, proposed Scheduled Maintenance Plans, proposed Inventory Plans, or other aspects of the Maintenance Services or Control Center Services. The E&O Committee is entitled to employ the services of one or more of the Responsible Entities to provide such services and the cost thereof shall constitute a Maintenance Cost or Control Center Cost, as applicable. 8.9 Owner Obligations Several . The obligation of each Owner to make payments to the applicable Responsible Entities under this Agreement is a several (and not joint) obligation (to the extent of its Ownership Percentage). The failure of either Owner to pay any amount for which it is obligated hereunder will not relieve any other Owner from its several payment obligations hereunder. 8.10 Funding for Extraordinary Events . If: (i) upon the occurrence of a Material Adverse Event or the necessity of other Unscheduled Maintenance Services or (ii) Maintenance Provider desires to take advantage of discounts, rebates or similar economic advantages, and in each case, the expenditures resulting from such causes are materially in excess of the amounts it usually and customarily incurs before invoicing, then such Maintenance Provider may request the Management Committee to direct the Owners to make the estimated funds needed for such purposes available to such Maintenance Provider. The Management Committee will act within five (5) Business Days of its receipt of a Maintenance Provider's written request accompanied by reasonable documentation and support. If the Management Committee so directs, the Owners shall deposit the estimated amount as determined by the Management Committee within seven (7) Business Days of receipt by each Owner of a notice specifying the estimated amount needed. 8.11 Metering and Compensation for the Project. If an Owner reasonably determines that it is being adversely impacted by losses on the Transmission Grid due to the metering and compensation arrangements of the Project, the Parties shall use commercially reasonable efforts to negotiate and agree upon an equitable allocation of responsibility and losses and update Appendix A accordingly. ARTICLE 9 MAJOR CONSTRUCTION EVENTS; OTHER MAJOR EVENTS 9.1 Undertaking Major Construction Events . The Owners and the Maintenance Provider recognize that the Transmission Grid is dynamically evolving and, during the Term, Major Construction Events are likely to occur. The Management Committee is empowered under the Project Ownership Agreement to determine, in the best interests of the Owners, the most efficient and cost-effective approach to undertaking Major Construction Events. The Maintenance Provider, as part of the Maintenance Services, will consult and cooperate with the Management Committee as reasonably necessary to allow the Management Committee to plan and implement Major Construction Events. The Management Committee will select the Person(s) that will undertake such construction and will negotiate the terms and conditions of any necessary agreements. 9.2 Payments . Notwithstanding anything to the contrary herein, a Maintenance Provider is not expected to advance (subject to reimbursement) amounts that at any time in the aggregate exceed Five Hundred Thousand Dollars ($500,000) in connection with the performance of the Maintenance Services hereunder, including the cost of Major Construction Events. Accordingly, the Management Committee and a Maintenance Provider shall agree to an acceptable funding mechanism as promptly as reasonably possible upon a Maintenance Provider's notification to the Management Committee that there is a reasonable likelihood that such limit could be exceeded. It is the express intent of the Owners that a Maintenance Provider will not be expected to bear the working capital costs of funding Maintenance Services at any time in excess of the limitation set forth in this Section 9.2. ARTICLE 10 REPRESENTATIONS AND WARRANTIES 10.1 Representations and Warranties of Each Responsible Entity . Each Responsible Entity, on and as of the Effective Date, makes the following representations and warranties, which representations and warranties survive the execution and delivery of this Agreement: 10.1.1 Organization and Good Standing . It is, as set forth in the preamble to this Agreement, a corporation organized, existing and in good standing under the laws of the state of its formation or incorporation, as the case may be, and is authorized to conduct business in each state in which authorization may be required to perform its obligations under this Agreement. 10.1.2 Power and Authority . It has the power and authority to enter into and perform this Agreement and is not prohibited from entering into this Agreement or discharging and performing all covenants and obligations on its part to be performed under and pursuant to this Agreement. 10.1.3 Authorization . It has taken all action required by Applicable Law and its governing documents, including its charter, in order to approve, execute and deliver this Agreement. 10.1.4 No Violation . The execution and delivery of this Agreement by it, the performance by it of its obligations hereunder and the consummation by it of the transactions contemplated herein do not and will not: (i) contravene any Applicable Law in effect as of the Effective Date or any Order in effect as of the Effective Date of any Governmental Body or arbitrator having jurisdiction over it or its Property or (ii) result in a breach or violation of any of the terms and provisions of, or constitute a default under, any indenture, mortgage, deed of trust or other agreement in effect as of the Effective Date and to which it is a party or by which it or its Property is bound. 10.1.5 Approvals and Consents .
